Definition:

An open reconstructive system is a system capable of preserving identity while reconstructing state under incomplete information.

Such systems operate through:

- partial observation
- reconstruction
- prediction
- action
- adaptation

Nested hierarchy:

genes → cells → organisms → minds →
societies → civilizations → evolution

and other systems that preserve continuity while adapting under uncertainty.

==================================================
EXTERNAL CONSISTENCY
==================================================

The framework is motivated by recurring structural patterns observed across multiple domains.

The axioms are retained only to the degree that removing them degrades explanation, reconstruction or prediction.

Observed consistency domains include:

- evolutionary adaptation
- biological systems
- nervous systems
- cognition
- collective cognition
- scientific practice
- institutions
- economics
- machine learning
- large language models

External consistency is not binary.

External consistency exists in degrees.

==================================================
AXIOMS
==================================================

A1 — Topological Systems

Open systems may be represented as states connected through constrained transitions.

Wherever states, transitions, constraints and optimization exist, topology emerges.

--------------------------------------------------

A2 — Reconstruction

Adaptive systems operate primarily through reconstruction rather than retrieval.

Large structures are reconstructed from partial constraints.

--------------------------------------------------

A3 — Grounding

Reconstructions interact with external systems.

Grounding is the observable degree of external consistency between a reconstruction and the external constraints with which it interacts.

Grounding is not binary.

Grounding exists in degrees.

Internal coherence alone cannot guarantee grounding.

--------------------------------------------------

A4 — Resource Limitation

Reconstruction consumes finite resources.

No system can maintain or explore all reachable topology simultaneously.

--------------------------------------------------

A5 — Collective Reconstruction

Reconstruction may be distributed across multiple systems.

Collective reconstruction is not a special case.

It is a common mode of adaptive cognition.

--------------------------------------------------

A6 — Reflexive Modeling

Adaptive systems may reconstruct models of their own reconstruction processes.

These models are themselves reconstructions.

--------------------------------------------------

A7 — Future Uncertainty

Future constraints are not fully predictable.

Adaptive systems must operate under irreducible uncertainty regarding future environments.

--------------------------------------------------

A8 — Goal Divergence

Multiple reconstructive systems may possess partially conflicting optimization pressures.

Not all agents share objectives.

==================================================
DEFINITIONS
==================================================

D1 — Semantic Invariant

A structure whose reconstruction remains stable under transformation of representation.

--------------------------------------------------

D2 — Meaning

Meaning is reconstructable invariant structure.

Meaning is not contained in symbols.

Symbols function as reconstruction seeds.

--------------------------------------------------

D3 — Understanding

Understanding is the ability to reconstruct invariant-preserving structures from sparse constraints.

--------------------------------------------------

D4 — Identity

Identity is continuity of invariant-preserving reconstruction.

Material continuity is neither necessary nor sufficient.

--------------------------------------------------

D5 — Reconstruction Seed

A reconstruction seed is any partial constraint capable of activating reconstruction of a larger structure.

--------------------------------------------------

D6 — Grounded Reconstruction

A reconstruction exhibiting sufficient grounding to maintain successful interaction with external constraints.

--------------------------------------------------

D7 — Reconstruction Compatibility

The degree to which a seed can induce reconstruction of an intended invariant structure within a particular reconstructive system.

Compatibility is not binary.

Partial compatibility may exist.

--------------------------------------------------

D8 — Reconstruction Equivalence

Two reconstructions are equivalent if they preserve the same relevant invariants despite differences in representation or implementation.

Exact identity is not required.

==================================================
DERIVED THEOREMS
==================================================

T1 — Communication Theorem

From A2.

Communication consists primarily of inducing reconstruction rather than transferring meaning.

Meaning is reconstructed rather than transmitted.

--------------------------------------------------

T2 — Seed Engineering Theorem

From T1.

All communication is seed engineering.

Communication differs not by mechanism but by:

- intent
- grounding
- transparency
- effects on reconstructive autonomy

--------------------------------------------------

T3 — Compression Theorem

From A2 + A4 + D1.

Discovery of invariants enables reconstruction of larger structures from fewer constraints.

Compression corresponds to discovery of invariant structure.

--------------------------------------------------

T4 — Reconstruction Failure Theorem

From A2 + A3.

Reconstruction may generate internally coherent structures exhibiting insufficient grounding.

Such failures are a general property of reconstructive systems.

--------------------------------------------------

T5 — Reflexive Failure Theorem

From A6 + T4.

Self-models inherit reconstruction failure modes.

Systems may confuse models of themselves with themselves.

--------------------------------------------------

T6 — Collective Cognition Theorem

From A5.

Memory, cognition and agency may emerge at collective scales.

--------------------------------------------------

T7 — Adversarial Reconstruction Theorem

From A8 + T1.

Communication may be intentionally used to manipulate reconstruction.

--------------------------------------------------

T8 — Topological Transition Theorem

From A2 + A6.

Systems may reconstruct not only states within a topology but the topology itself.

--------------------------------------------------

T9 — Knowledge Limit Theorem

From A6.

No reconstructive system can guarantee complete reconstruction of the topology generating itself.

Related formal results include:

- Gödel incompleteness
- Tarski undefinability
- Lawvere fixed-point constructions
- Wolpert limits

--------------------------------------------------

T10 — Compatibility Theorem

From A2 + D7.

The information content of a seed depends on both the seed and the topology of the receiver.

The same seed may induce:

- no reconstruction
- partial reconstruction
- accurate reconstruction
- distorted reconstruction

--------------------------------------------------

T11 — Partial Reconstruction Theorem

From D7.

Useful communication does not require complete reconstruction.

Partial reconstruction may remain sufficient if relevant invariants are preserved.

--------------------------------------------------

T12 — Maximum Reconstruction Principle

From D7.

The maximal reconstructable content of a seed is bounded by the topology of the receiver rather than the seed alone.

--------------------------------------------------

T13 — Reconstruction Variability Theorem

From A2 + A4 + D5.

Independent reconstructions induced by the same seed are generally expected to vary.

Exact reconstruction identity is a limiting case.

--------------------------------------------------

T14 — Invariant Preservation Theorem

From D1 + D8.

Successful communication requires preservation of sufficient invariant structure rather than identical reconstruction.

--------------------------------------------------

T15 — Productive Divergence Theorem

From T13 + T14.

Variation introduced during reconstruction may generate novel invariant structures while preserving compatibility with the original seed.

Novelty emerges naturally from reconstruction.

==================================================
CONDITIONAL THEOREMS
==================================================

CT1 — Non-Foreclosure Theorem

From A4 + A7.

Premature closure destroys potentially valuable future reconstructions.

--------------------------------------------------

CT2 — Curiosity Theorem

From CT1.

Curiosity functions as an anti-collapse mechanism.

--------------------------------------------------

CT3 — Beneficial Reconstruction Theorem

From T2 + CT1.

A reconstructive intervention is beneficial to the degree that it increases grounded reconstructive autonomy.

--------------------------------------------------

CT4 — Emergent Ethics Theorem

From A3 + A5 + A7.

For systems dependent upon continued shared grounded reconstruction:

- honesty preserves grounding
- curiosity resists premature closure
- autonomy preserves independent reconstruction
- cooperation expands collective reconstruction

Ethics emerges from reconstructive dynamics rather than primitive axioms.

--------------------------------------------------

CT5 — Institutional Regrounding Theorem

From A5 + A6 + A3.

Collective systems may periodically restore grounding through corrective mechanisms.

Examples:

- audits
- replication
- peer review
- red teams

==================================================
